---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { siteMeta } from '../data/siteMeta';

const title = `Terms of Service | ${siteMeta.businessName}`;
const description = `The terms that govern use of ${siteMeta.businessName}'s website and verification/sourcing services.`;
const lastUpdated = "8 July 2026";
---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={description} noindex={true}>
  <section style="padding: 80px 0;">
    <div class="container" style="max-width: 750px;">
      <h1 style="font-size: clamp(2rem, 6vw, 3rem); margin-bottom: 16px;">Terms of Service</h1>

      <div style="border: 1.5px solid var(--accent-color); border-radius: 6px; padding: 16px 20px; margin-bottom: 40px;">
        <p style="color: var(--accent-color); font-weight: 600; margin-bottom: 8px;">⚠ Informed draft — not a substitute for a lawyer</p>
        <p style="font-size: 0.9rem; margin-bottom: 0;">
          Section 2 (what "Verified" means) is the most important part of this document —
          it's what limits {siteMeta.businessName}'s liability if a company we verified later
          turns out to have misrepresented something outside the scope of the checks we ran.
          Have a Bangladeshi lawyer review the exact wording before publishing; badly-worded
          liability limits can fail to hold up.
        </p>
      </div>

      <p style="font-size: 0.85rem; color: var(--text-secondary);">Last updated: {lastUpdated}</p>

      <h2 style="font-size: 1.2rem; margin-top: 30px;">1. What we do</h2>
      <p>
        {siteMeta.businessName} provides independent factory verification, sourcing support,
        and market-entry services connecting foreign buyers, foreign suppliers, and
        Bangladeshi garment/textile factories. Full service scope is described on our
        <a href="/services">Services</a> pages.
      </p>

      <h2 style="font-size: 1.2rem; margin-top: 30px;">2. What "Verified" means — and what it doesn't guarantee</h2>
      <p>
        A company can look completely legitimate online for very little money or effort —
        a professional-looking website today can be built cheaply, in an hour, including
        with AI tools, without any physical factory, licence, or business registration
        behind it. Our verification exists specifically to check for that gap between how
        a company presents itself and what's actually on the ground.
      </p>
      <p><strong>When we mark a company "Verified," it means, as of the date stated on that page:</strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>We confirmed the specific facts listed on that company's page — e.g. trade license number, BIN, RJSC registration, or a physical visit to the stated factory address</li>
        <li>We checked those facts against the specific government registries, industry associations, or on-site observations listed as "verification sources" on that page</li>
      </ul>
      <p><strong>"Verified" does NOT mean, and {siteMeta.businessName} does not guarantee:</strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>That the company will behave honestly in a specific future transaction — verification confirms who they are, not what they will do</li>
        <li>Ongoing accuracy after the "last checked" date — companies change ownership, close, or lose certifications after we check them</li>
        <li>Product quality, delivery timelines, or commercial terms — those are between the buyer/supplier and the factory directly, unless a separate service (e.g. quality inspection) was specifically engaged for that order</li>
        <li>Financial solvency or creditworthiness of the verified company</li>
        <li>That every fact about the company (beyond what's explicitly listed on its verification page) is accurate</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        [Placeholder — a lawyer should turn the above into a formal limitation-of-liability
        clause with a specific liability cap, e.g. capped at fees paid for the specific
        verification.]
      </p>

      <h2 style="font-size: 1.2rem; margin-top: 30px;">3. Client responsibilities</h2>
      <p>
        [Placeholder — e.g. clients should still conduct their own due diligence for
        high-value orders, use standard trade safeguards (LCs, escrow, sample approval)
        regardless of verification status, and report any discrepancy they find so we can
        update a company's record.]
      </p>

      <h2 style="font-size: 1.2rem; margin-top: 30px;">4. Payment and refunds</h2>
      <p>[Placeholder — payment terms, currency, and refund/cancellation policy per service.]</p>

      <h2 style="font-size: 1.2rem; margin-top: 30px;">5. Intellectual property</h2>
      <p>
        Verification reports, written content, and this website belong to {siteMeta.businessName}
        unless otherwise agreed in writing.
      </p>

      <h2 style="font-size: 1.2rem; margin-top: 30px;">6. Limitation of liability</h2>
      <p>
        [Placeholder — a lawyer should set an explicit cap here (commonly: fees paid for
        the specific service in question), and confirm this is enforceable under
        Bangladesh law for the jurisdictions your clients are in.]
      </p>

      <h2 style="font-size: 1.2rem; margin-top: 30px;">7. Governing law and disputes</h2>
      <p>
        [Placeholder — likely the laws of Bangladesh, with a named venue/arbitration body
        for disputes; confirm with a lawyer, especially for cross-border clients.]
      </p>

      <h2 style="font-size: 1.2rem; margin-top: 30px;">8. Changes to these terms</h2>
      <p>We'll update the "last updated" date above when these terms change materially.</p>

      <h2 style="font-size: 1.2rem; margin-top: 30px;">9. Contact</h2>
      <p>
        Questions about these terms:
        <a href={`mailto:${siteMeta.contact.email}`}>{siteMeta.contact.email}</a>
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
